title: For Sale/Trade:  NORINCO CUSTOM 1911 5"
postcontent: Heres somthing special unlike the endless pages of glocks and ars. This is my norco custom 70s import that i built myself. Your first impression is norinco? Thats a chinese gun. BUT anyone who knows 1911s knows these are special guns. Nvrmnd where its made. Besides that most guns are imported from somehere. But heres the thing, they no longer import these so the ones that are here are it. Second the steel on these norcos are made from melted down tools and the like. VERY VERY high quality steel. Alot of guys that shoot competitively seek these out for custom builds. Well i didnt build mine to race but i did build it for protection. I striped it down and left only 3 stock parts on it besides the frame. The sights, because i dont care for night sights i like combat sights and these are already dead on. Second is the barrel because its already a match barrel it comes amazingly fitted and is accurate as hell. Third is the trigger because i like the small solid combat gi trigger. Now the rest of the parts including the hammer, hammer spring, sear, beaver tail, mainspring housing all of it is WILSON COMBAT. so basically heres the run down. I wanted a 100% reliable full size hair trigger accurate punisher 45 and i built it myself. Designed it perfectly to be a man stopper. It shoots any size 45 ball or hollow. The trigger is extemely light and crisp. Absolutely no failures of any kind. Not even before the tune up. Full length tungsten guide rod. Look i can go on and on but put simply its the best 1911 ive ever shot. By far. Ive had kimbers, colts, rocks, all those other brands and honestly those guns are the reason i built this 1. Yea ive had kimbers fail. Any other 1911 ive had to run wc mags to get it to work. My gun will run on 10$ colt mags. Ive put about 6-700 rnds of all sorts with no probs at all. The only downside i see is that it is heavy. Remember its made from high quality real steal from the good ol days. But on the other hand it helps to control recoil. Just depends on how you look at it. Now ive never shot a dan wesson or republic forge or wilson combat but i have to believe my gun will run with any of them. Its smooth as silk the recoil is just a dull push. The recovery and follow up shot is very natural and fast. Its basicly a custom wilson combat on a norco frame. Now heres the thing im just seeing whats out there. Im not desperate i dont need the money. This gun is my baby. I can build a 1911 with my eyes closed its very safe and 100% reliable. I wont come down. I wont trade it for no junk. But i am open to all kinds of offers. Ars, glocks, anything but its gotta be fair. Keep in mind how rare and special this gun is. Even colts are run of the mill. This gun is custom tuned. Email only for now. Thanks ppl i hope you all can appreciate as much as i do.

postcontent:
The Rogers Super-Stoc™ (commonly called the Super Stock) is the ultimate refinement in AR/M4 stock technology. The Rogers Super-Stoc™ is the most stable, collapsible stock available due to the innovative cam-lock system developed by Bill Rogers, famed shooting instructor, inventor of holsters, target systems, and other related products, and his staff of engineers. The cam-lock system completely removes any slop or play inherent with collapsible stocks. Once the desired stock position has been selected, the stock can be locked down solid simply by clicking the cam-lock lever upward. Pressing the quick-release lever will disengage both the cam-lock, and the detent pin, allowing you to quickly readjust the stock position. The innovative Rogers Super-Stoc™ also removes the guesswork involved with buffer tube sizes. Our stock will fit both a Mil-Spec sized buffer tube as well as a Commercial sized buffer tube with a few simple adjustments. Weighing in at only 7.3 oz, it is among the lightest stocks available, but rugged enough to pass a 36", fully loaded drop test. The Rogers Super-Stoc™ is simply the best collapsible stock for your AR style rifle.

MAKE: Ruger
MODEL: Bearcat Shopkeeper
SKU NUMBER: 0915
STOCK NUMBER: RUKSBCBH-3 Lipsey Exclusive

STOCK STYLE & FINISH: Stainless Finish w/ Wood Grips
BARREL FINISH: Stainless

OVERALL LENGTH: 8”

TWIST: 1:16
EXTRAS: Birdshead Gripframe, Crescent Ejector Rod, Button Head Cylinder Pin

Some Lipsey Exclusive guns happen fairly fast, others take some time. The Bearcat Shopkeeper is one gun that has been on the drawing table for several years. It all started with a visit by Lipsey to one of our biggest and most loyal dealers in Alabama. He showed them a beautiful little 3" barreled Ruger Bearcat. Everyone agreed it would make for a great Lipsey's Exclusive, and after talking to Ruger, they agreed to take a look at it.
Ruger decided to produce a round butt or birdshead type frame to go along with the 3" barrel. In addition to the 3" barrel and birdshead gripframe, they had to use a couple of other unique features to make it all work. Due to the short barrel, Ruger had to use a "button head" cylinder pin and a crescent shape ejector rod so that the spent cases could easily be extracted from the cylinder. Ruger is also using a steel ejector rod housing that matches the rest of the gun verses the aluminum one used on the standard Bearcats.
Even though it took 3 years, the wonderful engineers at Ruger made it happen and now we have a true "Shopkeeper" size Ruger Bearcat.
This is one of those guns that once you put it in your hands, you will have to get one.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Springfield EMP 9mm 1911
postcontent:
Springfield EMP 9mm 1911. This a stainless slide aluminum framed officer size 1911 from Springfield. The EMP is unique, Springfield didn't just take a .45 caliber frame and mangle a magazine to hold 9mm. They started with the 9mm built a magazine in the correct size and dimensions they built a slightly shorter grip to fit it.

The gun has been reliable for me. Only problems with liberty ammunition light weight JHP. Ate hydrashock just fine and fed about 20 Speer Gold Dot without issue. I love the gun but shoot mostly Glock in USPSA and the grip angle difference is proving to be a problem. I trust the gun but not myself enough to EDC it. Which is really what this gun was built for.
